<section xml:id="sec_sequences">
  <title>Defining a Sequence</title>
  <p>
    The shortest way to list the terms in a sequence is using the $ symbol in Maple.
    As an example, we may wish to list the elements of the sequence
    <me>
      \displaystyle\left\lbrace3k^2+2\right\rbrace_{k=0}^3
    </me>.
    This should give four integers that follow the form of <m>3k^2+2</m> from index <m>k=0</m> up to <m>k=3</m>.
    <idx><h>sequences and series</h><h>$ notation</h></idx>
  </p>
  <p>
    A dollar symbol is used after the expression of a generic term of the sequence, followed by specifying an interval for the index.
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>3*k^2+2 $ k=0..3;</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle 2,\,5,\,14,\,29
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    The index does not have to start at zero. Here are five integers of the sequence <m>\left\lbrace2k^2-k\right\rbrace_{k=1}^5</m>:
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>2*k^2-k $ k=1..5;</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle 1,\,6,\,15,\,28,\,45
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    We can also list the terms in a sequence by using the <c>seq()</c> command.
    This command essentially performs the same operation as the $ symbol.
    Here is that same sequence again, using the <c>seq()</c> command.
    <idx><h>sequences and series</h><h>seq</h></idx>
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>seq(2*k^2-k, k=1..5);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle 1,\,6,\,15,\,28,\,45
    </me>
  </p>
</section>